## 2. Architectural Shift — Counter vs. Event Source

### Current Architecture: "Update-a-Counter"

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[QuestionCard] -->|1. saveAnswer| B[INSERT user_question_history]
    A -->|2. incrementUsage| C[RPC increment_daily_usage]
    C -->|UPDATE| D[user_profiles.questions_answered_today]
    B -.->|"No relationship"| D
```

**Problems**: Two independent writes, no transactional guarantee, counter can drift, no audit trail for the counter itself.

### Recommended: Event-Sourced Model

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[QuestionCard] -->|1. Single atomic write| B["INSERT answer_events (immutable log)"]
    B -->|Trigger| C["Materialized View / Aggregate"]
    C -->|Provides| D[Dashboard Stats]
    C -->|Provides| E[Daily Counter]
    C -->|Provides| F[Theme Mastery]
```

**Key principle**: The `answer_events` table becomes the **single source of truth**. All counters, stats, and dashboards are **derived** from it via materialized views, CTEs, or database triggers. You never increment a counter directly — you always derive it with `COUNT(*) FROM answer_events WHERE answered_date = CURRENT_DATE`.

### Why Event Sourcing is Required

| Concern | Counter Model | Event-Sourced |
|---|---|---|
| **Audit trail** | ❌ No history of counter changes | ✅ Every event is timestamped and immutable |
| **Data recovery** | ❌ Counter drifts = permanent data loss | ✅ Re-derive from events at any time |
| **Multi-dimensional analytics** | ❌ One counter per metric = N columns | ✅ Slice events by any dimension (time, theme, banca) |
| **Debugging** | ❌ "Why is the counter at 47?" | ✅ "Show me the 47 events" |
| **Scalability** | ❌ UPDATE contention on user_profiles row | ✅ Append-only INSERTs are lock-free |

